# Cursor Cost Efficiency Protocol

> **Before starting work, complete the Pre-Execution Summary.**
> For **Medium** or **High** complexity tasks, read `.cursor/skills/sf-cost-efficiency-reference/SKILL.md` before proceeding.

## Pre-Execution Summary

Before starting any substantive work, state:

1. **Estimated complexity:** Low / Medium / High
2. **Mode:** Chat / Plan / Agent
3. **Subagents needed:** None / org-agent (fast) / research-agent (inherits) / dev-agent (inherits) / review-agent (fast)
4. **Parallelizable:** Yes / No — [which agents can run concurrently]

## Complexity Gate

| Complexity | Criteria | Actions |
|---|---|---|
| **Low** | Single file, straightforward change, no org interaction | Proceed directly; no subagents; no Plan mode needed |
| **Medium** | 2-5 files, some reasoning needed, may need org verification | Use Plan mode first; prefer direct tool calls over subagents for simple checks. **Load sf-cost-efficiency-reference.** |
| **High** | 5+ files, architecture decisions, org verification + design, cross-cutting concerns | Use Plan mode with capable parent model; break into subtasks; delegate mechanical work to `model: fast` subagents. **Load sf-cost-efficiency-reference.** |

## Rule Conflict Priority

When multiple rules are simultaneously active: **(1) always-applied rules** take baseline precedence; **(2) glob-scoped rules** take precedence by specificity (narrower glob wins); **(3) skill files** (on-demand) apply last. If a conflict cannot be resolved, ask the user.

## Context Continuity

- **Never re-read files already in context** just because a new skill was loaded. Skills are additive, not resetting.
- **Never re-ask clarified questions.** Consult prior turns before asking the user again.
- **After conversation summary/compaction:** Treat the summary as authoritative. Do not re-derive conclusions already covered.
- **Prefer `??` (null coalescing)** over `!= null` ternaries in Apex. Prefer `?.` (safe navigation) for nullable chains.
- **Build Maps upfront** from query results before iterating. Never nest loops to find matching records — use `Map.get()`.

